This adds the `fun_prop` attribute to all declarations in `Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Complex.LogDeriv` where doing so does not result in an error message. See [this Zulip thread](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/fun_prop.20attribute.20for.20Complex.2Elog.20lemmas.3F/near/482347068).

(No changes by 10‚Åπ or more instructions anywhere in either direction.)

:v: MichaelStollBayreuth can now approve this pull request. To approve and merge a pull request, simply reply with `bors r+`. More detailed instructions are available [here](https://bors.tech/documentation/getting-started/#reviewing-pull-requests).
~~Please don't merge yet, let me test something.~~

I think it's fine to only tag the simple forms.

bors merge
If you tag the compositional lemmas such as `DifferentiableAt.clog`, I think these are superfluous (and - I believe - causes `fun_prop` to do extra work).

`DifferentiableAt.clog` was exactly what I tagged to make `fun_prop` work in my use case, but it seems that you are right, and it suffices to tag the non-compositional lemmas.
Will remove the attribute from the others.

@fpvandoorn per your comment to me on your recent `fun_prop` PR, we should actively *not* mark `differentiableAt_log` with the `fun_prop` tag for performance reasons, right? and the same for any of these "leaf" nodes, like `hasStrictFDerivAt_log_real`? If that's the case, then we need to remove all those `fun_prop` attributes from leaf nodes across the library.

I am confused about it though, because I would have expected that due to the discrimination tree indexing, these specific versions wouldn't be tried unless everything matched, and hence there would be essentially no performance cost.
But how can `fun_prop` then derive that compositions/combinations involving `Complex.log` are differentiable etc.?

@MichaelStollBayreuth: I think `fun_prop` is actually quite good, and if you either tag `differentiable_log` or `Differentiable.log` it will succeed. @j-loreaux said that the latter was better to tag. I don't know if that is true, but maybe he has an example where it is better.
But my original message was intended to mean: *only* keep `fun_prop` for the compositional lemmas, not for the atomic ones, but my message was ambiguous.

However, if you tag both, `fun_prop` fails exponentially slowly: https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/fun_prop.20fails.20exponentially.20slowly
This problem is so pervasive in Mathlib, that tagging these two more lemmas won't really hurt until we have a proper solution for all of Mathlib.

@fpvandoorn  Ah OK, I read "these" as referring to the compositional ones.
So I switch to tagging the compositional lemmas instead? (Or, if it is simpler, feel free to push to this branch if you like.)
Yeah, keep only the compositional ones (or keep all of them, since `fun_prop` failing will take ~infinity time anyway - the exponential behavior was much worse than I expected).
